{"slug": "augury", "root": "augury", "category": "divination", "gloss": "the art of reading omens", "definition": "*Augury* is the reading of omens in the flight, feeding, and cries of birds. Where the *haruspex* consults entrails and the *hydromancer* a bowl of water, the augur watches the sky, judging whether the gods approve a proposed act rather than forecasting a fixed future.", "history": "The word descends from Latin *augurium*, the divination by birds practiced by the college of *augures* who opened every Roman public act. Rome's elaborate norms did not survive the ancient world intact; as Kieckhefer notes, medieval Europe kept only a primitive sort of popular augury that read the future from the calls of birds, the number of a crow's croaks. Moralists then folded it into their catalogues of forbidden arts alongside soothsaying and the interpretation of dreams. The Roman ritual survives fossilized in the word *inauguration*.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Kieckhefer, Magic in the Middle Ages", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Clark, Thinking with Demons", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. augury (Latin augurium)", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Latin", "origin": "Latin augurium 'divination by birds'", "first": "late 14c.", "note": "The state art of reading omens in bird-flight; every Roman public act opened with it, and 'inauguration' still does.", "hook": "Rome's birds ran the government."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 0, "oracle_total": 0, "in_flavor_cards": 0, "in_oracle_cards": 0, "name_match_count": 9, "by_variant": {}, "first_year": 2008, "colors": {"R": 2, "U": 9, "B": 1, "W": 1}, "by_year": {"2008": 1, "2013": 1, "2015": 1, "2016": 1, "2021": 1, "2022": 2, "